{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592875"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:19:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:19:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15279"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15279"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.16,0.77,0.06,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7970"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69023"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7970"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15279"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54480"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5146"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19397"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute pancreatitis is a potentially severe condition characterised by inflammation of the pancreas. Under normal conditions, pancreatic enzymes are activated only after reaching the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of acute pancreatitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enzyme activation occurs only in the duodenum","Inflammation precedes enzyme activation","Premature enzyme activation occurs within pancreatic cells","Lipase activation is the initiating event","Trypsin inhibits enzyme activation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key pathophysiological feature of acute pancreatitis is \u003Cstrong\u003Epremature enzyme activation within pancreatic cells\u003C/strong\u003E. This inappropriate intracellular activation leads to autodigestion of pancreatic tissue and inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnzyme activation occurs only in the duodenum\u003C/strong\u003E - While this is normal physiology, in pancreatitis enzymes are inappropriately activated within the pancreas\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammation precedes enzyme activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Enzyme activation is the initiating event that triggers inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipase activation is the initiating event\u003C/strong\u003E - Trypsinogen activation to trypsin is the key initial step\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrypsin inhibits enzyme activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Trypsin actually promotes activation of other pancreatic enzymes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe premature activation of digestive enzymes within pancreatic tissue can be triggered by various causes, most commonly gallstones and alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Premature activation of pancreatic enzymes within pancreatic acinar cells leads to autodigestion and inflammation in acute pancreatitis.","Gallstones and alcohol are the two most common causes of acute pancreatitis.","The pathological cascade begins with inappropriate activation of trypsinogen to trypsin within pancreatic tissue."],"references":["Szatmary P, Grammatikopoulos T, Cai W, Huang W, Mukherjee R, Halloran C, Beyer G, Sutton R. Acute Pancreatitis: Diagnosis and Treatment. Drugs. 2022 Aug;82(12):1251-1276. doi: 10.1007/s40265-022-01766-4. Epub 2022 Sep 8. PMID: 36074322; PMCID: PMC9454414","Mederos MA, Reber HA, Girgis MD. Acute Pancreatitis: A Review. JAMA. 2021 Jan 26;325(4):382-390. doi: 10.1001/jama.2020.20317. Erratum in: JAMA. 2021 Jun 15;325(23):2405. doi: 10.1001/jama.2021.5789. PMID: 33496779","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54480"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15279"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54480"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T20:36:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T20:37:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7970"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69023"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes"